{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-be4cd923b10e0e5a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "data from a single native Efik speaker. Recordings were cap-         audio was resampled to 16kHz mono to maintain consistency\ntured using a wireless microphone in a quiet indoor environment      across the corpus and align with common neural TTS training\nto minimize background noise and ensure acoustic consistency.        configurations.\nThe final corpus consists of 2,632 utterances segmented at the            Basic signal cleaning procedures were applied to improve\nsentence level.                                                      acoustic consistency. Leading and trailing silence segments\n     The recording materials were drawn from Efik novels, folk-      were trimmed while preserving natural prosodic boundaries. To\ntales, and educational texts in order to provide lexical diversity   prevent truncation of final phonemes, which is important for\nand broad domain coverage. Care was taken to include var-            tonal realization, approximately 60-100 milliseconds of trailing\nied sentence structures and tonal patterns to support supervised     silence were retained at the end of each utterance. This ensured\nspeech synthesis under low-resource conditions.                      that sentence-final acoustic cues were not clipped during seg-\n     Although Efik is spoken by 1.5 million native speakers          mentation.\n[6], obtaining a high-quality speech dataset suitable for neural          Text preprocessing involved orthographic normalization\nText-to-Speech training presents significant challenges. Pub-        to remove irrelevant punctuation marks and non-speech sym-\nlicly available audio resources often contain background music,      bols. Sentence boundaries were preserved to maintain natural\nenvironmental noise, or overlapping speech, rendering them un-       prosodic structure. All transcripts were manually verified for\nsuitable for controlled acoustic modeling. Furthermore, many         consistency with the spoken content.\nexisting recordings lack explicit usage consent for computa-              The final corpus of 2,632 utterances was partitioned into\ntional research and TTS development, limiting their applicabil-      training, validation and test sets as summarized in Table 1.\nity.\n     These constraints necessitated the collection of a dedicated,                      Split        Utterances\nconsented, and acoustically controlled dataset specifically de-                         Train                1,975\nsigned for supervised Efik TTS development.                                             Validation             264\n                                                                                        Test                   393\n4.1. Data Labeling                                                                   Table 1: Dataset split statistics.\n\nWe initially explored automatic forced alignment to generate\ntime-aligned transcriptions for the recorded Efik speech data.\nHowever, this approach proved unreliable due to the absence of\n                                                                     4.4. Statistical Analysis of Dataset\nrobust Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) models for Efik.\nPretrained multilingual models, including Whisper [21] and           The Efik TTS corpus consists of 2,632 utterances with a total\nXLS-R [22], produced highly inaccurate transcriptions when           duration of approximately 3.08 hours. The utterances vary in\n\flength from 0.48 seconds to 15.94 seconds, with an average du-              VITS (Variational Inference with Adversarial Learning for\nration of 4.21 seconds and a median duration of 3.49 seconds.          End-to-End TTS) [23] is a single-stage model that directly gen-\nFigure 1 shows the distribution of audio clip durations, where         erates raw audio waveforms from text using a conditional vari-\nthe y-axis represents the number of clips and the x-axis repre-        ational autoencoder combined with normalizing flows and ad-\nsents duration in seconds.                                             versarial learning.\n                                                                            MMS-TTS [24] is part of the Multilingual Speech Synthe-\n                                                                       sis (MMS) framework, leveraging pretrained multilingual rep-\n                                                                       resentations to improve synthesis quality in low-resource lan-\n                                                                       guages. Its architecture enables cross-lingual transfer, which is\n                                                                       useful for Efik given the lack of large-scale TTS corpora.\n                                                                            SpeechT5 [25] is a transformer-based sequence-to-\n                                                                       sequence TTS model that unifies speech and text representa-\n                                                                       tions. It allows flexible encoding of linguistic and acoustic fea-\n                                                                       tures.\n                                                                            Orpheus-TTS [26] is a neural TTS model optimized for\n                                                                       waveform fidelity and naturalness. It uses adversarial training\n                                                                       techniques to improve the realism of generated audio.\n\n                                                                                            6. Experiments\n                                                                       The four TTS models were fine-tuned with hyperparameters op-\n                                                                       timized for low-resource, single-speaker Efik TTS. VITS was\n                                                                       trained for 50 epochs with a learning rate of 2e-4, a batch size\n                                                                       of 4, and the Adam optimizer. MMS-TTS was trained for 50\n                                                                       epochs with a learning rate of 2e-5, a batch size of 16, and\n         Figure 1: Distribution of audio clips duration.\n                                                                       the AdamW optimizer, leveraging multilingual pretraining to\n                                                                       improve performance in low-resource settings. SpeechT5 was\n    The corresponding text corpus contains 23,986 word tokens          trained with a smaller learning rate of 1e-5 and a batch size of 4,\nwith a vocabulary of 3,276 unique words. Utterance lengths             and was allowed to run up to 2,500 epochs with early stopping\nrange from 1 to 33 words, with an average of 9.11 words per ut-        to ensure stable convergence under limited data conditions. A\nterance. Figure 2 illustrates the distribution of utterance lengths,   dropout rate of 0.1 was applied to reduce overfitting. Orpheus-\nwith the y-axis representing the number of clips and the x-axis        TTS was trained for 50 epochs with a learning rate of 2e-5 and\nrepresenting the number of words per utterance.                        a batch size of 8. All models were trained on a single NVIDIA\n                                                                       A100 GPU using mixed-precision training to improve computa-\n                                                                       tional efficiency and memory utilization. Early stopping based\n                                                                       on validation loss was applied to mitigate overfitting given the\n                                                                       limited size of the dataset. The single-speaker configuration\n                                                                       provided acoustic consistency across recordings, which is ben-\n                                                                       eficial for learning stable spectral and prosodic representations,\n                                                                       particularly in a tonal language such as Efik.\n                                                                            Since MMS-TTS had no pretrained checkpoint for Efik, we\n                                                                       initialized it using a Yoruba checkpoint and extended its vocab-\n                                                                       ulary and embedding to include Efik-specific characters such as\n                                                                       o. and ñ. Similarly, VITS and SpeechT5 required updates to their\n                                                                       embeddings and vocabularies to accommodate these charac-\n                                                                       ters, whereas Orpheus-TTS worked without modification. De-\n                                                                       spite these efforts, all models struggled to correctly pronounce\n                                                                       words containing ñ highlighting the challenge of representing\n                                                                       rare phonemes in extremely low-resource settings. In contrast,\n                                                                       for the o. character, MMS-TTS, SpeechT5, and Orpheus-TTS\n                                                   